ce:section.ce:para:
Figures 2C and 2D show the contact stress distribution and the normal displacements of the coating at the interface for PEO polymer, respectively, under different values of stack pressure. As expected, both the peak pressure and peak normal displacement values do not scale linearly with the applied stack pressure; indeed, the peak contact stress increases from 0.51 MPa under a stack pressure of 10 kPa, to 0.88 MPa under a stack pressure of 100 kPa. Similarly, the peak normal displacement at the interface ranges from 0.036 μm (10 kPa) to 0.072 μm (100 kPa). Notably, a saturation of the peak contact stress for stack pressure values is reported above 100 kPa stack pressure. Indeed, as expected from contact mechanics studies, the number of asperities involved in the contact increases by increasing the contact mean pressure; beyond a certain threshold, the additional load resulting from increased mean pressure values is almost entirely carried by the new asperities getting into contact. Under these conditions, the peak contact stress is no longer affected by the stack pressure value. Moreover, by comparing the peak contact stress (0.88 MPa) with the yield stress of lithium metal (16 MPa, according Zhang et al.
   9
), we conclude that no plasticity occurs on the metal side. The peak contact stress near the Li-polymer interface is much smaller than the Li-garnet interface (several hundreds of MPa stress from the 3D stress mapping
   101
) since the modulus of polymers is much smaller than those garnet SSEs.

(note that in the interface between pure oxide SEs and lithium metal, the mechanics contribution mainly comes from the contact elastoplaticity of lithium metal
                           60
                        ).
